{{Designation list | designation1 = Ramsar | designation1_offname = Elephant Marsh | designation1_date = 1 July 2017 | designation1_number = 2308<ref>{{Cite web|title=Elephant Marsh|website=[[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar]] Sites Information Service|url=https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/2308|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>}} '''Elephant Marsh''' lies on the flood plain of the Lower [[Shire River]] in the African country of [[Malawi]] between the towns of [[Chikwawa]] and [[Nsanje]]. The marsh varies in size from 150 to 450 square miles depending on the flow of the Shire and [[Ruo River|Ruo]] rivers and has no permanent boundary. In some places, floating mats of vegetation are so thick boat travel is nearly impossible. The Ruo River, the largest tributary of the Shire and the southeastern boundary between Malawi and [[Mozambique]], merges with the Shire in the Elephant Marsh.
The marsh was named by [[David Livingstone]] in 1859, who counted as many as 800 elephants in one sighting. Today the elephants are largely gone, but the Elephant Marsh supports a large number of aquatic birds. Crocodiles are also very common. The marsh is similar to swampy [[Lake Chilwa]], located two hundred miles to the north. Boat trips through Elephant Marsh can be arranged from nearby [[Lengwe National Park]].<ref>http://www.malawitourism.com/pages/attractions/the_attraction.asp?AttractionsID=28</ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
{{coord missing|Malawi}}
[[Category:Geography of Southern Region, Malawi]] [[Category:Wetlands of Malawi]] [[Category:Wetlands of Africa]] [[Category:Marshes]] [[Category:Ramsar sites in Malawi]]

'''Equivalent effective stratospheric chlorine''' (EESC) provides an estimate of the total effective amount of [[halogens]] ([[chlorine]] and [[bromine]]) in the [[stratosphere]]. It is calculated from emission of [[chlorofluorocarbon]] and related halogenated compounds into the [[troposphere]] (lower atmosphere) and their efficiency in contributing to stratospheric ozone depletion (ozone depletion potential, ODP), and by making assumptions on transport times into the upper atmosphere ([[stratosphere]]).<ref>Newman, P. A., Daniel, J. S., Waugh, D. W., and Nash, E. R.: A new formulation of equivalent effective stratospheric chlorine (EESC), Atmos. Chem. Phys., 7, 4537-4552, {{doi|10.5194/acp-7-4537-2007}}, 2007.</ref> This parameter is used to quantify man-made [[ozone depletion]] and its changes with time. As a consequence of the [[Montreal Protocol]] and its amendments phasing out ozone-depleting substances (ODS), the EESC reached maximum in the late 1990s and is now slowly decreasing.
==References== {{Reflist|1}}
[[Category:Ozone depletion]]

The following [[sweet pea]] [[cultivars]] have gained the [[Royal Horticultural Society]]'s [[Award of Garden Merit]]. They are [[annual plant|annual]]s grown as twining climbers, with flowers in pastel shades from white through pink to blue and deep purple. There are several bi-colours. Several cultivars are scented to a greater or lesser degree. Sweet peas can be badly affected by [[aphid]]s, slugs and snails. [[File:P1000291 Lathyrus odoratus (Dorothy Eckford) (Leguminosae) Flower.JPG|thumb|’Dorothy Eckford’, [[Cambridge University Botanic Garden]]]] {| class="wikitable sortable" |- ! Variety !! Colour !! Height !! Fragrance !! Ref |- | America || white/purple || 1.8m || medium || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=3313|title=RHS Plant Selector Lathyrus odoratus 'America' AGM |work=RHS Gardening|publisher=Royal Horticultural Society|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> |- | Bobby's Girl || pale salmon pink || 1.8m || medium || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=3317|title=RHS Plant Selector Lathyrus odoratus 'Bobby's Girl' AGM |work=RHS Gardening|publisher=Royal Horticultural Society|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> |- | Bristol || pale violet || 1.7m || strong || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=3318|title=RHS Plant Selector Lathyrus odoratus 'Bristol' AGM |work=RHS Gardening|publisher=Royal Horticultural Society|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> |- | Cathy || white || 2.0m || medium || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=4765|title=RHS Plant Selector Lathyrus odoratus 'Cathy' AGM |work=RHS Gardening|publisher=Royal Horticultural Society|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> |- | Charlie's Angel || pale violet || 2.0m || strong || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.rhs.org.uk/plantselector/plant?plantid=3319|title=RHS Plant Selector Lathyrus odoratus 'Charlie's Angel' AGM |work=RHS Gardening|publisher=Royal Horticultural Society|accessdate=2012