{{Multiple issues|{{refimprove|date=July 2015}}{{lead missing|date=July 2015}}{{confusing|date=July 2015|reason=Context unclear.}} {{one source|date=July 2015}}}}
This article describes some extremes in the sky as a textual addition to the [[list of star extremes]] page.
==Brightness==
{| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! Title ! Object ! Date ! Data ! Comments ! Notes ! References ! See More |- style="background:lightgreen;" ! Brightest Star ([[visual magnitude]]) | [[Sun]] | ''prehistoric'' | m=-26.74 | | | | |- ! Brightest Star Outside the [[Solar System]] (visual magnitude) | [[Sirius]] (Alpha Canis Majoris) | ''prehistoric'' | m=−1.46 | Sirius is located in the [[Canis Major]] constellation. Also, It lies in the [[Southern Celestial Hemisphere]] | | | |- ! Brightest Star ([[absolute magnitude]]) | [[S Doradus]] | | M=-9.9 | | | | |- ! Faintest Star (visual magnitude) | | | | | | | |- ! Faintest Star (absolute magnitude) | | | | | | | |}
==Location== {| class="wikitable" border="1" |- ! [[File:Broad blank space.jpg|none|110px]] ! Title ! Object ! Date ! Declination ! Misc. Data ! Comments ! Notes ! References ! See More |- ! rowspan="2" | First Magnitude ! Northernmost Star | [[Capella]] | | +45° 59′ 52.768″ | | | | | |- ! Southernmost Star | [[Acrux]] | | −63° 05′ 56.7343″ | | | | | |- ! rowspan="2" | Second Magnitude ! Northernmost Star | [[Polaris]] | | +89° 15′ 50.8″ | | | | | |- ! Southernmost Star | [[Beta Hydri]] | | –77° 15′ 15.2860″ | | | | | |- ! rowspan="2" | Third Magnitude ! Northernmost Star | [[Gamma Cephei]] | | +77° 37′ 56.19″ | | | | | |- ! Southernmost Star | [[Alpha Apodis]] | | −79° 02′ 41.1032 | | | | | |- ! rowspan="2" | Fourth Magnitude ! Northernmost Star | [[Delta Ursae Minoris]] | | 86° 35′ 11.2584 | | | | | |- ! Southernmost Star | [[Delta Octantis]] | | −83° 40′ 04.3868 | | | | | |- ! rowspan="2" | Fifth Magnitude ! Northernmost Star | [[24 Ursae Minoris]] | | +86° 58′ 04.9″ | | | | | |- ! Southernmost Star | [[Sigma Octantis]] | | -88° 57′ 23″ | | | | | |- |}
The southern hemisphere consists of more 1st magnitude stars (mv brighter than +1.6) (12) than the northern (11).
Due to [[precession]] this will change over the centuries, by AD 13800, [[Vega]] will be only 4 degrees from the North Pole, at the same time Canopus will be 10 degrees from the South pole. At that time, the number of bright stars in the northern hemisphere will be only 6 while 17 in the southern. Moreover, due to [[proper motion]] some nearby stars like [[Arcturus]] or [[Alpha Centauri]] will be displaced several degrees. About AD 6400 Alpha Centauri will pass 1 degree from Beta Centauri.<ref name="Stellarium">calculated by Stellarium 0.13, an open source sky mapping app. http://www.stellarium.org</ref>
At BC 3400, [[Achernar]] was only 8 degrees from the South Pole.<ref name="Stellarium"/>
The greatest concentration of bright stars is around Orion. Within a circle of 60 degrees radius around a point in Monoceros at RA 6:30, DE 5ºS, 11 stars of magnitude +1.6 or brighter occur: [[Capella]], [[Pollux (star)|Pollux]], [[Castor (star)|Castor]], [[Regulus]], [[Procyon]], [[Sirius]], [[Adhara]], [[Canopus]], [[Rigel]], [[Betelgeuse]] and [[Aldebaran]]. No other part of the sky consists of so many bright stars. The entire sky consists of 23 such stars. Narrowing the circle to 50 degrees and moving the center to the midway point of Capella and Canopus (a few degrees east of Orion's belt) will still consist of 9 stars leaving out only Regulus.
Within a much smaller circle of 10 degrees radius from [[Alnilam]], the center Orion belt star, 5 stars of mag +2.2 or brighter occur of which 70 are available in the entire sky.
The most 'remote' 1st magnitude star from another 1st magnitude star is Fomalhaut which is nearest to Achernar (39 degrees) and Antares which is nearest to Alpha Centauri (also 39 degrees). All other 1st magnitude stars are closer than that angular distance to another 1st magnitude star.
