[[File:Echium plantagineum2.jpg|thumb|220px|[[Echium plantagineum|Paterson's Curse]] has been responsible for the deaths of many horses.]] Many plants are poisonous to [[equine]]s; the species vary depending on location, climate, and grazing conditions. In many cases, entire [[genus|genera]] are poisonous to equines and include many species spread over several continents. Plants can cause reactions ranging from [[laminitis]] (found in horses bedded on shavings from [[black walnut]] trees), [[anemia]], [[kidney disease]] and kidney failure (from eating the wilted leaves of [[red maple]]s), to [[cyanide]] poisoning (from the ingestion of plant matter from members of the genus ''[[Prunus]]'') and other symptoms. Members of genus ''Prunus'' have also been theorized to be at fault for [[Mare Reproductive Loss Syndrome|mare reproductive loss syndrome]].<ref name=Trees>{{cite journal|url=http://www.thehorse.com/ViewArticle.aspx?ID=3411&src=VW|title=Which Trees are Toxic?|journal=The Horse|author=Cable, Christina|date=2002-04-01|accessdate=2010-12-07|registration=yes}}</ref> Some plants, including [[Taxus|yews]], are deadly and extremely fast-acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.horseandhound.co.uk/horse-care-index/1370/36101.html|title=Poisonous Plants: Yew|publisher=Horse & Hound|date=2001-06-25|accessdate=2010-12-12|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318233401/http://www.horseandhound.co.uk/horse-care-index/1370/36101.html|archivedate=18 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Several plants, including [[nightshade]], become more toxic as they wilt and die, posing a danger to horses eating dried [[hay]] or plant matter blown into their pastures.<ref name=King>{{cite journal|url=http://www.thehorse.com/ViewArticle.aspx?ID=3058|title=Poisonous Plants|journal=The Horse|author=King, Marcia|date=2001-05-01|accessdate=2010-12-07|registration=yes}}</ref>
The risk of animals becoming ill during the [[fall (season)|fall]] is increased, as many plants slow their growth in preparation for winter, and equines begin to browse on the remaining plants. Many toxic plants are unpalatable, so animals avoid them where possible. However, this is not always the case; [[locoweed]]s, for example, are addictive and once a horse has eaten them, it will continue to eat them whenever possible, and can never be exposed to them again. When a toxic plant is ingested, it can be difficult to diagnose, because exposure over time can cause symptoms to occur after the animal is no longer exposed to the plant. Toxins are often metabolized before the symptoms become obvious, making it hard or impossible to test for them.<ref name=DeLong>{{cite journal|url=http://www.thehorse.com/viewarticle.aspx?id=12869|journal=The Horse|registration=yes|accessdate=2010-12-06|author=DeLong, Jodi|date=2008-10-10|title=Poisonous Plant Risk Increases as Pasture Grass Goes Dormant}}</ref> Hungry or thirsty horses are more likely to eat poisonous plants, as are those pastured on [[overgrazing|overgrazed lands]].<ref name=Ohio>{{cite web|url=http://ohioline.osu.edu/b762/b762_24.html|title=Horse Nutrition|publisher=Ohio State University|accessdate=2010-12-08|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101206031741/http://ohioline.osu.edu/b762/b762_24.html|archivedate=6 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Animals with mineral deficiencies due to poor diets will sometimes seek out poisonous plants.<ref name=Utah>{{cite web|url=http://www.msuextension.org/ruralliving/Dream/PDF/Equine_poison.pdf |title=Poisonous Plants and Equines |publisher=Utah State University |author1=Israelsen, Clark E. |author2=McKendrick, Scott S. |author3=Bagley, Clell V. |date=2006-10-01 |accessdate=2010-12-08 |format=PDF |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110112023355/http://www.msuextension.org/ruralliving/Dream/PDF/Equine_poison.pdf |archivedate=12 January 2011 |df= }}</ref> Poisonous plants are more of a danger to livestock after [[wildfires]], as they often regrow more quickly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://msuextension.org/publications/OutdoorsEnvironmentandWildlife/4455.pdf|title=After Wildfire|author=Knight, James E.|publisher=Montana State University|accessdate=2010-12-15|date=2002}}</ref>
==Poisonous plants== [[File:Starr 030405-0063 Ageratina adenophora.jpg|thumb|Crofton weed (''Ageratina adenophora'') (flowers and leaves)]] [[File:Nerium oleander.jpg|thumb|The deadly ''Nerium'' [[oleander]]]] {| class="wikitable sortable" |- ! Scientific name ! Common name ! Notes ! class="unsortable"| References |- |''[[Abrus precatorius]]'' |Crab's eye |Also known as precatory bean, rosary pea, or jequirity bean |<ref name=DiTomaso/> |- |''[[Acer rubrum]]'' |Red maple, also known as swamp or soft maple |Toxic compounds are gallic acid and tannins. |<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.horsedvm.com/poisonous/red-maple/|title=HorseDVM Toxic Plants for Horses {{!}} Red maple|last=LLC|first=HorseDVM|website=HorseDVM|language=en|access-date=2017-07-09}}</ref><ref name=DeLong/> |- |''[[Adonis microcarpa]]'' |Pheasant's eye |Often found in hay. |<ref name="EJM"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.horsedvm.com/poisonous/summer-pheasants-eye/|title=HorseDVM Toxic Plants for Horses {{!}} Summer pheasant's eye|last=LLC|first=HorseDVM|website=HorseDVM|language=en|access-date=2017-07-09}}</ref> |- |''[[Aesculus hippocastanum]]'' |Horse chestnut |Also known as buckeye |<ref name=King/> |- |''[[Ageratina]]'' |Snakeroots |Known poisonous species include ''[[Ageratina adenophora]]'' (Crofton weed, causes Tallebudgera horse disease) and ''[[Ageratina altissima]]'' (white snakeroot) |<ref name=King/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dpi.qld.gov.au/cps/rde/xchg/dpi/hs.xsl/4790_7246_ENA_HTML.htm|title=Crofton weed|accessdate=2010-12-06|author=Jordan, Sonia|date=2010-10-26|publisher=The State of Queensland}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> |- |''[[Aleurites]]'' |Tung oil tree | |<ref name=DiTomaso/> |- |''[[Amsinckia intermedia]]'' |Fiddleneck |Contains pyrrolizidine alkaloids |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cecalaveras.ucdavis.edu/toxic.htm|title=Toxic Plants in Your Hay and Pasture|publisher=University of California – Davis|accessdate=2010-12-07|deadu